  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs during
loop-vectorization while VPlanTransforms tries to simplify a VP recipe by folding
live-in operands via InstSimplifyFolder. Specifically, it attempts to fold an
ExtractElement recipe where the vector operand is actually a scalar constant (i32
0). InstructionSimplify's simplifyExtractElementInst immediately casts the
operand's type to VectorType, asserting that the operand is a vector. Because the
operand is scalar, an assertion fires and opt aborts.\n\nThis matches the IR
comment in the reproducer: \"Make sure we don't try to fold a
Instruction::ExtractElement ir<0>, ir<0>, since we can't materialize the live-in
for the vector operand.\"\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The first transformation
point identified is simplifyExtractElementInst in InstructionSimplify.cpp.\n- The
backtrace shows tryToFoldLiveIns calling InstSimplifyFolder::FoldExtractElement
with ill-typed operands (Vec is i32 0).\n- Debugger locals show Ops[0] == 0x...
(i32 0), Ops[1] is an index, and Opcode == 62 (ExtractElement). The immediate
assert in simplifyExtractElementInst casts Vec->getType() to VectorType.\n\n3.
Root Cause Analysis:\nVPlanTransforms::tryToFoldLiveIns assumes that if all
operands are live-ins, it can hand them to InstSimplifyFolder. However, for
certain VP recipes (like ExtractElement), the VP graph may have scalar live-ins
in places where the instruction semantics require a vector (e.g., an
extractelement of a vector). Passing such ill-typed operands to
InstSimplifyFolder leads to InstructionSimplify assuming well-typed IR and
asserting.\n\nTherefore, the bug is that tryToFoldLiveIns does not verify operand
types for instructions with strict type requirements (ExtractElement,
InsertElement, etc.) before attempting to fold.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n-
File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanTransforms.cpp\n- Location:
tryToFoldLiveIns switch handling of InsertElement and ExtractElement (lines
983\u2013987 in provided snapshot).\n- Change: Add type guards to ensure the
vector operand is actually vector-typed before calling InstSimplifyFolder. If
not, bail out and return nullptr so no folding is attempted.\n\nProposed patch
(conceptual):\n\nReplace existing cases:\n  case Instruction::InsertElement:\n
return Folder.FoldInsertElement(Ops[0], Ops[1], Ops[2]);\n  case
Instruction::ExtractElement:\n    return Folder.FoldExtractElement(Ops[0],
Ops[1]);\n\nWith guarded versions:\n  case Instruction::InsertElement: {\n    if
(!isa<VectorType>(Ops[0]->getType()))\n      return nullptr;\n    return
Folder.FoldInsertElement(Ops[0], Ops[1], Ops[2]);\n  }\n  case
Instruction::ExtractElement: {\n    if (!isa<VectorType>(Ops[0]->getType()))\n
return nullptr;\n    return Folder.FoldExtractElement(Ops[0], Ops[1]);\n
}\n\nRationale:\n- Prevents calling
simplifyExtractElementInst/simplifyInsertElementInst with ill-typed operands,
preserving the precondition that the IR being folded is well-typed.\n- Matches
the intent spelled out in the reproducer comment: do not try to fold
extractelement ir<0>, ir<0> when you can't materialize the vector live-in.\n-
Keeps the change localized to VPlanTransforms, which is the origin of the
incorrect folding request, rather than weakening assertions in the more general
InstSimplify code.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by
VPlanTransforms::tryToFoldLiveIns attempting to fold an ExtractElement with
scalar live-ins, violating type invariants expected by InstSimplify and
triggering an assertion. Adding vector type checks before calling the Folder for
ExtractElement (and symmetrically for InsertElement) avoids ill-typed folding,
preventing the assertion and aligning behavior with the reproducer's expectation.
This fix prevents the abort while preserving all valid simplifications.",
